Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded after 2.6 per cent in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate rate, which it considers would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: inflation must be "discussed" in order to rule out the need for action at a later stage.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a twelve-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Increased food and energy prices were responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products were also significantly more expensive in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
