Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "enhancement of existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and the non-gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the political leaders: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, promote extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention paid by the domestic and foreign media, "have seriously damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extremely right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organisations called the "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"It is common for these groups to define themselves as civil organizations, while they openly brag about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (catastrophe protection, national defence, protection of order), citing the unfitness of the police, the army, or the state itself," they said.
And further: All this is done according to the method that tries to disguise various political aspirations as a bourgeois initiative, based on the political and party discontent of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association is not merely a means of circumventing legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration with the court - it is also a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risk-enhancing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries.Some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirming its own anti-Hungary policy.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region" - they said.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
According to reports, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the extreme right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard were the mass riots of the Roma, which took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU immediately took the events as an occasion for the creation of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organisation is "national protection".
