Banks Want to Cope with Crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money from each other.
For example, the US Fed is sending 40 billion dollars at auction, another 24 making them loose for the European and Swiss Central Banks.
After the attacks of 11 September, it is the first time that the central banks of the individual states have agreed on such a coordinated approach to counter or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the biggest difficulties of the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," wrote in a report for its customers Bernard Baumohl of the consulting company Economic Outlook Group.
"The coordinated action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the US from 65% to about 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unserved loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
"The central banks must have been really afraid of what can still happen when they decided to do so," said the chief economist of ABN Amro, Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he continued.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, possibly with an impact on economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to reduce the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used for lending money between banks, after they failed to do so.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid of lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further reduction in interest rates," said Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting of the Reuters agency.
Some analysts believe that this step by central banks is contributing to the heating up of the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the real estate market in the US.
