A Serious Memory
After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, have not yet been consulted, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. on the request of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, the eleven states responsible for managing them, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Dangerous information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health status of forced laborers, Reto Meistern, head of these archives, which are administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental obstruction of some deportation victims.
The lists of inmates of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still handle tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, explained Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Antisemitism of the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
