In addition to the modernisation of financial markets, the MIFID, which is redefining the Investment Services Regulation, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, an increase in the entitlement to control by the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and the promotion of cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows both specialised firms and natural or legal persons to provide financial advice and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the consulting companies which are affiliated with investment and brokerage companies of securities.
It also expands the number of financial transaction execution systems so that the multilateral securities trading systems and the internationalisation of trading orders will be added to the regulated circulation markets, which will eventually compete with the current economic operators.
The law obliges investment companies to identify the priorities of their company profile, the confrontation and forms of dealing with risks on the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the control task of CNMV.
