New fears about gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is raging between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia's gas exports to the European Union (EU) are channelled through Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU states.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," said Anatoli Kinakh, Ukraine's Minister of Economy, Reuters.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish National Health Service must improve controls on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said one member of the control body.
The recommendation of the chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish public health service had no precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were correctly carried out on a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after driving an off-road vehicle through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in Britain.
It is expected that the Public Health Service will carry out checks prior to hiring foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency has no jurisdiction to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the main auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found references to these controls in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation guidelines to a high degree before hiring, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health service employees is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to the employment of potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that the NHS Scotland's current pre-employment tests work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards have problems identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation also found that established control procedures were predominantly followed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passports, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
The secretary for health Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the light of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines on pre-employment control investigations would be reflected by all employees, including those from abroad, whose publication is planned next month.
