These aren't Warhol's boxes
Those who connect the terms Sweden and wooden boxes think of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
Most of the ninety-four "Stockholm" Brillo boxes listed there are fakes.
After a few months ago, the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes of 1968, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately hundred other Brillo Boxes of the "Type Stockholm" that are circulating on the international art market.
The prehistory is interlaced, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which were rightfully incorporated into the history of art and auctions at the time as authorised original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has examined not only the six museum-owned Brillo boxes but also three from Swedish private ownership, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their chipboard plates were first primed and sanded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press board with a paint roll without primer - besides, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to another conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, however, the Authentication Board announced to investigate the "serious accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebellious soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers have given up hiding in a hotel in Manila, demanding the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He could not be responsible for bloodshed, said the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and electoral fraud, reporters in the hotel.
Governmental soldiers had previously stormed the hotel under tear gas.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been hiding in the building for hours.
About half of them went to trial on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He used the trial to suddenly settle with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who were supposed to guard him, had apparently defected to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government troops blocked the district around the noble hotel.
The President called an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National security adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who once commanded the elite squad of the Scout Rangers, said other army units wanted to join the march shortly.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the President for Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by allegations of corruption for months.
As early as 2003, Manila's financial district was the main venue for the attempted mutiny of around 200 military personnel against Arroyo.
After almost 24 hours, the uprising failed due to the army's refusal to join.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes major shareholder at Versatel
United Internet has secured a share of more than 20 percent of the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday evening.
You now hold 20.05 percent of the share capital.
A takeover had previously been speculated.
The option to increase the share of Versatel is kept open.
With this step, the German DSL market is to be consolidated, United Internet announced.
Earlier on Wednesday, there had already been speculation about an entry, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator by a further 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house considers the shares to be only a third party, it said on the financial market.
On the previous day, United Internet already had a stake in the mobile communications company Drillisch with almost 10 percent.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth 106.4 million euros.
United Internet has bought 5.15 million shares for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started discussions on marketing cooperation for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," said a United Internet spokesperson.
The two companies have established the MSP joint venture to take over the competitor Freenet.
For the time being, the two companies want to satisfy themselves with a share of a good ten percent of Freenet and not make use of their right to acquire another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet announced on Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase their shareholding in Freenet AG, they said.
Discussions between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
Poker around Freenet, which has been going on for months and is difficult to understand, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and complete connection customers.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch previously held directly 6.01 percent of the Freenet shares.
It had now been agreed that Drillisch would contribute another around four percent.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
